SPEAKER: SCENE I
TEXT: Enter Francisco and Barnardo, two sentinels.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Who’s there?

SPEAKER: FRANCISCO
TEXT: Nay, answer me. Stand and unfold yourself.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Long live the King!

SPEAKER: FRANCISCO
TEXT: Barnardo?

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: He.

SPEAKER: FRANCISCO
TEXT: You come most carefully upon your hour.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: ’Tis now struck twelve. Get thee to bed, Francisco.

SPEAKER: FRANCISCO
TEXT: For this relief much thanks. ’Tis bitter cold,

SPEAKER: FRANCISCO
TEXT: And I am sick at heart.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Have you had quiet guard?

SPEAKER: FRANCISCO
TEXT: Not a mouse stirring.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Well, good night.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: If you do meet Horatio and Marcellus,

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: The rivals of my watch, bid them make haste.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Enter Horatio and Marcellus.

SPEAKER: FRANCISCO
TEXT: I think I hear them. Stand, ho! Who is there?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Friends to this ground.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: And liegemen to the Dane.

SPEAKER: FRANCISCO
TEXT: Give you good night.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: O, farewell, honest soldier, who hath reliev’d you?

SPEAKER: FRANCISCO
TEXT: Barnardo has my place. Give you good-night.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Holla, Barnardo!

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Say, what, is Horatio there?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: A piece of him.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Welcome, Horatio. Welcome, good Marcellus.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: What, has this thing appear’d again tonight?

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: I have seen nothing.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Horatio says ’tis but our fantasy,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: And will not let belief take hold of him

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Touching this dreaded sight, twice seen of us.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Therefore I have entreated him along

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: With us to watch the minutes of this night,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: That if again this apparition come

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: He may approve our eyes and speak to it.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Tush, tush, ’twill not appear.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Sit down awhile,

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: And let us once again assail your ears,

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: That are so fortified against our story,

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: What we two nights have seen.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Well, sit we down,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: And let us hear Barnardo speak of this.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Last night of all,

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: When yond same star that’s westward from the pole,

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Had made his course t’illume that part of heaven

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Where now it burns, Marcellus and myself,

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: The bell then beating one—

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Peace, break thee off. Look where it comes again.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Enter Ghost.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: In the same figure, like the King that’s dead.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Thou art a scholar; speak to it, Horatio.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Looks it not like the King? Mark it, Horatio.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Most like. It harrows me with fear and wonder.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: BARNARDO

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: It would be spoke to.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Question it, Horatio.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: What art thou that usurp’st this time of night,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Together with that fair and warlike form

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: In which the majesty of buried Denmark

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Did sometimes march? By heaven I charge thee speak.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: It is offended.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: See, it stalks away.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Stay! speak, speak! I charge thee speak!

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: ’Tis gone, and will not answer.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: How now, Horatio! You tremble and look pale.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Is not this something more than fantasy?

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: What think you on’t?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Before my God, I might not this believe

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Without the sensible and true avouch

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Of mine own eyes.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Is it not like the King?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: As thou art to thyself:

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Such was the very armour he had on

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: When he th’ambitious Norway combated;

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: So frown’d he once, when in an angry parle

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: He smote the sledded Polacks on the ice.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: ’Tis strange.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Thus twice before, and jump at this dead hour,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: With martial stalk hath he gone by our watch.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: In what particular thought to work I know not;

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: But in the gross and scope of my opinion,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: This bodes some strange eruption to our state.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Good now, sit down, and tell me, he that knows,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Why this same strict and most observant watch

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: So nightly toils the subject of the land,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: And why such daily cast of brazen cannon

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: And foreign mart for implements of war;

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Why such impress of shipwrights, whose sore task

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Does not divide the Sunday from the week.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: What might be toward, that this sweaty haste

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Doth make the night joint-labourer with the day:

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Who is’t that can inform me?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: That can I;

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: At least, the whisper goes so. Our last King,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Whose image even but now appear’d to us,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Was, as you know, by Fortinbras of Norway,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Thereto prick’d on by a most emulate pride,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Dar’d to the combat; in which our valiant Hamlet,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: For so this side of our known world esteem’d him,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Did slay this Fortinbras; who by a seal’d compact,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Well ratified by law and heraldry,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Did forfeit, with his life, all those his lands

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Which he stood seiz’d of, to the conqueror;

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Against the which, a moiety competent

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Was gaged by our King; which had return’d

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: To the inheritance of Fortinbras,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Had he been vanquisher; as by the same cov’nant

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: And carriage of the article design’d,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: His fell to Hamlet. Now, sir, young Fortinbras,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Of unimproved mettle, hot and full,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Hath in the skirts of Norway, here and there,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Shark’d up a list of lawless resolutes,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: For food and diet, to some enterprise

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: That hath a stomach in’t; which is no other,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: As it doth well appear unto our state,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: But to recover of us by strong hand

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: And terms compulsatory, those foresaid lands

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: So by his father lost. And this, I take it,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Is the main motive of our preparations,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: The source of this our watch, and the chief head

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Of this post-haste and rummage in the land.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: I think it be no other but e’en so:

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Well may it sort that this portentous figure

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: Comes armed through our watch so like the King

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: That was and is the question of these wars.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: A mote it is to trouble the mind’s eye.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: In the most high and palmy state of Rome,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: A little ere the mightiest Julius fell,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: The graves stood tenantless and the sheeted dead

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Did squeak and gibber in the Roman streets;

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: As stars with trains of fire and dews of blood,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Disasters in the sun; and the moist star,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Upon whose influence Neptune’s empire stands,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Was sick almost to doomsday with eclipse.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: And even the like precurse of fierce events,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: As harbingers preceding still the fates

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: And prologue to the omen coming on,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Have heaven and earth together demonstrated

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Unto our climatures and countrymen.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Re-enter Ghost.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: But, soft, behold! Lo, where it comes again!

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: I’ll cross it, though it blast me. Stay, illusion!

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: If thou hast any sound, or use of voice,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Speak to me.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: If there be any good thing to be done,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: That may to thee do ease, and grace to me,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Speak to me.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: If thou art privy to thy country’s fate,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Which, happily, foreknowing may avoid,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: O speak!

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Or if thou hast uphoarded in thy life

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Extorted treasure in the womb of earth,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: For which, they say, you spirits oft walk in death,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Speak of it. Stay, and speak!

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Stop it, Marcellus!

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Shall I strike at it with my partisan?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Do, if it will not stand.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: ’Tis here!

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: ’Tis here!

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: ’Tis gone!

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: We do it wrong, being so majestical,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: To offer it the show of violence,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: For it is as the air, invulnerable,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: And our vain blows malicious mockery.

SPEAKER: BARNARDO
TEXT: It was about to speak, when the cock crew.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: And then it started, like a guilty thing

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Upon a fearful summons. I have heard

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: The cock, that is the trumpet to the morn,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Doth with his lofty and shrill-sounding throat

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Awake the god of day; and at his warning,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Whether in sea or fire, in earth or air,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Th’extravagant and erring spirit hies

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: To his confine. And of the truth herein

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: This present object made probation.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: It faded on the crowing of the cock.

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Some say that ever ’gainst that season comes

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Wherein our Saviour’s birth is celebrated,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: The bird of dawning singeth all night long;

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: And then, they say, no spirit dare stir abroad,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: The nights are wholesome, then no planets strike,

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: No fairy takes, nor witch hath power to charm;

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: So hallow’d and so gracious is the time.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: So have I heard, and do in part believe it.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: But look, the morn in russet mantle clad,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Walks o’er the dew of yon high eastward hill.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Break we our watch up, and by my advice,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Let us impart what we have seen tonight

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Unto young Hamlet; for upon my life,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: This spirit, dumb to us, will speak to him.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Do you consent we shall acquaint him with it,

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: As needful in our loves, fitting our duty?

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Let’s do’t, I pray, and I this morning know

SPEAKER: MARCELLUS
TEXT: Where we shall find him most conveniently.

TEXT: The memory be green, and that it us befitted

TEXT: To bear our hearts in grief, and our whole kingdom

TEXT: Of this his nephew’s purpose, to suppress

TEXT: Out of his subject: and we here dispatch

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: With windlasses, and with assays of bias,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: By indirections find directions out.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: So by my former lecture and advice

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Shall you my son. You have me, have you not?

SPEAKER: REYNALDO
TEXT: My lord, I have.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: God b’ wi’ you, fare you well.

SPEAKER: REYNALDO
TEXT: Good my lord.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Observe his inclination in yourself.

SPEAKER: REYNALDO
TEXT: I shall, my lord.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And let him ply his music.

SPEAKER: REYNALDO
TEXT: Well, my lord.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Farewell.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Enter Ophelia.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: How now, Ophelia, what’s the matter?

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: Alas, my lord, I have been so affrighted.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: With what, in the name of God?

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: My lord, as I was sewing in my chamber,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: Lord Hamlet, with his doublet all unbrac’d,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: No hat upon his head, his stockings foul’d,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: Ungart’red, and down-gyved to his ankle,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: Pale as his shirt, his knees knocking each other,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: And with a look so piteous in purport

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: As if he had been loosed out of hell

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: To speak of horrors, he comes before me.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Mad for thy love?

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: My lord, I do not know, but truly I do fear it.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: What said he?

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: He took me by the wrist and held me hard;

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: Then goes he to the length of all his arm;

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: And with his other hand thus o’er his brow,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: He falls to such perusal of my face

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: As he would draw it. Long stay’d he so,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: At last,—a little shaking of mine arm,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: And thrice his head thus waving up and down,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: He rais’d a sigh so piteous and profound

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: As it did seem to shatter all his bulk

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: And end his being. That done, he lets me go,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: And with his head over his shoulder turn’d

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: He seem’d to find his way without his eyes,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: For out o’ doors he went without their help,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: And to the last bended their light on me.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Come, go with me. I will go seek the King.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: This is the very ecstasy of love,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Whose violent property fordoes itself,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And leads the will to desperate undertakings,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: As oft as any passion under heaven

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: That does afflict our natures. I am sorry,—

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: What, have you given him any hard words of late?

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: No, my good lord; but as you did command,

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: I did repel his letters and denied

SPEAKER: OPHELIA
TEXT: His access to me.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: That hath made him mad.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: I am sorry that with better heed and judgement

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: I had not quoted him. I fear’d he did but trifle,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And meant to wreck thee. But beshrew my jealousy!

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: It seems it is as proper to our age

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: To cast beyond ourselves in our opinions

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: As it is common for the younger sort

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: To lack discretion. Come, go we to the King.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: This must be known, which, being kept close, might move

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: More grief to hide than hate to utter love.

SPEAKER: SCENE II
TEXT: A room in the Castle.

SPEAKER: SCENE II
TEXT: Enter King, Queen, Rosencrantz, Guildenstern and Attendants.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Welcome, dear Rosencrantz and Guildenstern.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Moreover that we much did long to see you,

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: The need we have to use you did provoke

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Our hasty sending. Something have you heard

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Of Hamlet’s transformation; so I call it,

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Since nor th’exterior nor the inward man

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Resembles that it was. What it should be,

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: More than his father’s death, that thus hath put him

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: So much from th’understanding of himself,

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: I cannot dream of. I entreat you both

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: That, being of so young days brought up with him,

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: And since so neighbour’d to his youth and humour,

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: That you vouchsafe your rest here in our court

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Some little time, so by your companies

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: To draw him on to pleasures and to gather,

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: So much as from occasion you may glean,

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Whether aught to us unknown afflicts him thus

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: That, open’d, lies within our remedy.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: Good gentlemen, he hath much talk’d of you,

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: And sure I am, two men there are not living

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: To whom he more adheres. If it will please you

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: To show us so much gentry and good will

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: As to expend your time with us awhile,

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: For the supply and profit of our hope,

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: Your visitation shall receive such thanks

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: As fits a king’s remembrance.

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: Both your majesties

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: Might, by the sovereign power you have of us,

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: Put your dread pleasures more into command

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: Than to entreaty.

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: We both obey,

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: And here give up ourselves, in the full bent,

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: To lay our service freely at your feet

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: To be commanded.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Thanks, Rosencrantz and gentle Guildenstern.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: Thanks, Guildenstern and gentle Rosencrantz.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: And I beseech you instantly to visit

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: My too much changed son. Go, some of you,

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: And bring these gentlemen where Hamlet is.

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: Heavens make our presence and our practices

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: Pleasant and helpful to him.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: Ay, amen.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: Enter Polonius.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Th’ambassadors from Norway, my good lord,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Are joyfully return’d.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Thou still hast been the father of good news.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Have I, my lord? Assure you, my good liege,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: I hold my duty, as I hold my soul,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Both to my God and to my gracious King:

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And I do think,—or else this brain of mine

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Hunts not the trail of policy so sure

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: As it hath us’d to do—that I have found

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: The very cause of Hamlet’s lunacy.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: O speak of that, that do I long to hear.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Give first admittance to th’ambassadors;

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: My news shall be the fruit to that great feast.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Thyself do grace to them, and bring them in.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: He tells me, my sweet queen, that he hath found

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: The head and source of all your son’s distemper.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: I doubt it is no other but the main,

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: His father’s death and our o’erhasty marriage.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Well, we shall sift him.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Enter Polonius with Voltemand and Cornelius.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Welcome, my good friends!

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Say, Voltemand, what from our brother Norway?

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: Most fair return of greetings and desires.

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: Upon our first, he sent out to suppress

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: His nephew’s levies, which to him appear’d

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: To be a preparation ’gainst the Polack;

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: But better look’d into, he truly found

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: It was against your Highness; whereat griev’d,

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: That so his sickness, age, and impotence

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: Was falsely borne in hand, sends out arrests

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: On Fortinbras; which he, in brief, obeys,

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: Receives rebuke from Norway; and in fine,

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: Makes vow before his uncle never more

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: To give th’assay of arms against your Majesty.

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: Whereon old Norway, overcome with joy,

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: Gives him three thousand crowns in annual fee,

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: And his commission to employ those soldiers

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: So levied as before, against the Polack:

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: With an entreaty, herein further shown,

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: That it might please you to give quiet pass

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: Through your dominions for this enterprise,

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: On such regards of safety and allowance

SPEAKER: VOLTEMAND
TEXT: As therein are set down.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: It likes us well;

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: And at our more consider’d time we’ll read,

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Answer, and think upon this business.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Meantime we thank you for your well-took labour.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Go to your rest, at night we’ll feast together:.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Most welcome home.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: This business is well ended.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: My liege and madam, to expostulate

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: What majesty should be, what duty is,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Why day is day, night night, and time is time

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Were nothing but to waste night, day and time.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Therefore, since brevity is the soul of wit,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And tediousness the limbs and outward flourishes,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: I will be brief. Your noble son is mad.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Mad call I it; for to define true madness,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: What is’t but to be nothing else but mad?

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: But let that go.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: More matter, with less art.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Madam, I swear I use no art at all.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: That he is mad, ’tis true: ’tis true ’tis pity;

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And pity ’tis ’tis true. A foolish figure,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: But farewell it, for I will use no art.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Mad let us grant him then. And now remains

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: That we find out the cause of this effect,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Or rather say, the cause of this defect,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: For this effect defective comes by cause.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Thus it remains, and the remainder thus. Perpend,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: I have a daughter—have whilst she is mine—

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Who in her duty and obedience, mark,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Hath given me this. Now gather, and surmise.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: _To the celestial, and my soul’s idol, the most beautified Ophelia_—

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: That’s an ill phrase, a vile phrase; ‘beautified’ is a vile

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: phrase: but you shall hear.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: _these; in her excellent white bosom, these, &c._

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: Came this from Hamlet to her?

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Good madam, stay awhile; I will be faithful.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: _Doubt thou the stars are fire,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Doubt that the sun doth move,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Doubt truth to be a liar,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: But never doubt I love.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: O dear Ophelia, I am ill at these numbers. I have not art to reckon my

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: groans. But that I love thee best, O most best, believe it. Adieu.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Thine evermore, most dear lady, whilst this machine is to him,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: This in obedience hath my daughter show’d me;

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: And more above, hath his solicitings,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: As they fell out by time, by means, and place,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: All given to mine ear.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: But how hath she receiv’d his love?

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: What do you think of me?

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: As of a man faithful and honourable.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: I would fain prove so. But what might you think,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: When I had seen this hot love on the wing,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: As I perceiv’d it, I must tell you that,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Before my daughter told me, what might you,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Or my dear Majesty your queen here, think,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: If I had play’d the desk or table-book,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Or given my heart a winking, mute and dumb,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Or look’d upon this love with idle sight,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: What might you think? No, I went round to work,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And my young mistress thus I did bespeak:

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: ‘Lord Hamlet is a prince, out of thy star.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: This must not be.’ And then I precepts gave her,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: That she should lock herself from his resort,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Admit no messengers, receive no tokens.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Which done, she took the fruits of my advice,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And he, repulsed,—a short tale to make—

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Fell into a sadness, then into a fast,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Thence to a watch, thence into a weakness,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Thence to a lightness, and, by this declension,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Into the madness wherein now he raves,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And all we wail for.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Do you think ’tis this?

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: It may be, very likely.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Hath there been such a time, I’d fain know that,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: That I have positively said ‘’Tis so,’

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: When it prov’d otherwise?

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Not that I know.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Take this from this, if this be otherwise.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: If circumstances lead me, I will find

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Where truth is hid, though it were hid indeed

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Within the centre.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: How may we try it further?

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: You know sometimes he walks four hours together

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Here in the lobby.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: So he does indeed.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: At such a time I’ll loose my daughter to him.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Be you and I behind an arras then,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Mark the encounter. If he love her not,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: And be not from his reason fall’n thereon,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Let me be no assistant for a state,

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: But keep a farm and carters.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: We will try it.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Enter Hamlet, reading.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: But look where sadly the poor wretch comes reading.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Away, I do beseech you, both away

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: I’ll board him presently. O, give me leave.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: How does my good Lord Hamlet?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Well, God-a-mercy.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Do you know me, my lord?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Excellent well. You are a fishmonger.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Not I, my lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Then I would you were so honest a man.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Honest, my lord?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Ay sir, to be honest, as this world goes, is to be one man picked out

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: of ten thousand.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: That’s very true, my lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: For if the sun breed maggots in a dead dog, being a good kissing

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: carrion,—

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Have you a daughter?

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: I have, my lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Let her not walk i’ th’ sun. Conception is a blessing, but not as your

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: daughter may conceive. Friend, look to’t.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: How say you by that? [_Aside._] Still harping on my daughter. Yet he

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: knew me not at first; he said I was a fishmonger. He is far gone, far

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: gone. And truly in my youth I suffered much extremity for love; very

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: near this. I’ll speak to him again.—What do you read, my lord?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Words, words, words.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: What is the matter, my lord?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Between who?

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: I mean the matter that you read, my lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Slanders, sir. For the satirical slave says here that old men have grey

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: beards; that their faces are wrinkled; their eyes purging thick amber

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: and plum-tree gum; and that they have a plentiful lack of wit, together

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: with most weak hams. All which, sir, though I most powerfully and

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: potently believe, yet I hold it not honesty to have it thus set down.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: For you yourself, sir, should be old as I am, if like a crab you could

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: go backward.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Will you walk out of the air, my lord?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Into my grave?

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Indeed, that is out o’ the air. [_Aside._] How pregnant sometimes his

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: replies are! A happiness that often madness hits on, which reason and

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: sanity could not so prosperously be delivered of. I will leave him and

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: suddenly contrive the means of meeting between him and my daughter.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: My honourable lord, I will most humbly take my leave of you.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: You cannot, sir, take from me anything that I will more willingly part

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: withal, except my life, except my life, except my life.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: Fare you well, my lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: These tedious old fools.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Enter Rosencrantz and Guildenstern.

SPEAKER: POLONIUS
TEXT: You go to seek the Lord Hamlet; there he is.

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: My honoured lord!

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: My most dear lord!

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: My excellent good friends! How dost thou, Guildenstern? Ah,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Rosencrantz. Good lads, how do ye both?

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: As the indifferent children of the earth.

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: Happy in that we are not over-happy;

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: On Fortune’s cap we are not the very button.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Nor the soles of her shoe?

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: Neither, my lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Then you live about her waist, or in the middle of her favours?

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: Faith, her privates we.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: In the secret parts of Fortune? O, most true; she is a strumpet. What’s

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: the news?

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: None, my lord, but that the world’s grown honest.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Then is doomsday near. But your news is not true. Let me question more

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: in particular. What have you, my good friends, deserved at the hands of

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Fortune, that she sends you to prison hither?

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: Prison, my lord?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Denmark’s a prison.

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: Then is the world one.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: A goodly one; in which there are many confines, wards, and dungeons,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Denmark being one o’ th’ worst.

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: We think not so, my lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Why, then ’tis none to you; for there is nothing either good or bad but

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: thinking makes it so. To me it is a prison.

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: Why, then your ambition makes it one; ’tis too narrow for your mind.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: O God, I could be bounded in a nutshell, and count myself a king of

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: infinite space, were it not that I have bad dreams.

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: Which dreams, indeed, are ambition; for the very substance of the

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: ambitious is merely the shadow of a dream.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: A dream itself is but a shadow.

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: Truly, and I hold ambition of so airy and light a quality that it is

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: but a shadow’s shadow.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Then are our beggars bodies, and our monarchs and outstretch’d heroes

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: the beggars’ shadows. Shall we to th’ court? For, by my fay, I cannot

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: reason.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: We’ll wait upon you.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: No such matter. I will not sort you with the rest of my servants; for,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: to speak to you like an honest man, I am most dreadfully attended. But,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: in the beaten way of friendship, what make you at Elsinore?

SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
TEXT: To visit you, my lord, no other occasion.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Beggar that I am, I am even poor in thanks; but I thank you. And sure,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: dear friends, my thanks are too dear a halfpenny. Were you not sent

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: for? Is it your own inclining? Is it a free visitation? Come, deal

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: justly with me. Come, come; nay, speak.

SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
TEXT: What should we say, my lord?

SPEAKER: HAMLET

TEXT: Let me see. [_Takes the skull._] Alas, poor Yorick. I knew him,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Horatio, a fellow of infinite jest, of most excellent fancy. He hath

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: borne me on his back a thousand times; and now, how abhorred in my

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: imagination it is! My gorge rises at it. Here hung those lips that I

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: have kiss’d I know not how oft. Where be your gibes now? your gambols?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: your songs? your flashes of merriment, that were wont to set the table

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: on a roar? Not one now, to mock your own grinning? Quite chop-fallen?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Now get you to my lady’s chamber, and tell her, let her paint an inch

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: thick, to this favour she must come. Make her laugh at that.—Prithee,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Horatio, tell me one thing.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: What’s that, my lord?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Dost thou think Alexander looked o’ this fashion i’ th’earth?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: E’en so.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: And smelt so? Pah!

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: E’en so, my lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: To what base uses we may return, Horatio! Why may not imagination trace

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: the noble dust of Alexander till he find it stopping a bung-hole?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: ’Twere to consider too curiously to consider so.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: No, faith, not a jot. But to follow him thither with modesty enough,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: and likelihood to lead it; as thus. Alexander died, Alexander was

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: buried, Alexander returneth into dust; the dust is earth; of earth we

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: make loam; and why of that loam whereto he was converted might they not

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: stop a beer-barrel?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Imperious Caesar, dead and turn’d to clay,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Might stop a hole to keep the wind away.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: O, that that earth which kept the world in awe

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Should patch a wall t’expel the winter’s flaw.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: But soft! but soft! aside! Here comes the King.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Enter priests, &c, in procession; the corpse of Ophelia, Laertes and

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Mourners following; King, Queen, their Trains, &c.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: The Queen, the courtiers. Who is that they follow?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: And with such maimed rites? This doth betoken

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: The corse they follow did with desperate hand

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Fordo it own life. ’Twas of some estate.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Couch we awhile and mark.

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: What ceremony else?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: That is Laertes, a very noble youth. Mark.

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: What ceremony else?

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: Her obsequies have been as far enlarg’d

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: As we have warranties. Her death was doubtful;

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: And but that great command o’ersways the order,

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: She should in ground unsanctified have lodg’d

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: Till the last trumpet. For charitable prayers,

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: Shards, flints, and pebbles should be thrown on her.

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: Yet here she is allowed her virgin rites,

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: Her maiden strewments, and the bringing home

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: Of bell and burial.

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: Must there no more be done?

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: No more be done.

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: We should profane the service of the dead

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: To sing sage requiem and such rest to her

SPEAKER: PRIEST
TEXT: As to peace-parted souls.

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: Lay her i’ th’earth,

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: And from her fair and unpolluted flesh

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: May violets spring. I tell thee, churlish priest,

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: A minist’ring angel shall my sister be

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: When thou liest howling.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: What, the fair Ophelia?

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: I hop’d thou shouldst have been my Hamlet’s wife;

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: I thought thy bride-bed to have deck’d, sweet maid,

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: And not have strew’d thy grave.

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: O, treble woe

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: Fall ten times treble on that cursed head

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: Whose wicked deed thy most ingenious sense

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: Depriv’d thee of. Hold off the earth a while,

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: Till I have caught her once more in mine arms.

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: Now pile your dust upon the quick and dead,

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: Till of this flat a mountain you have made,

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: To o’ertop old Pelion or the skyish head

SPEAKER: LAERTES
TEXT: Of blue Olympus.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: What is he whose grief

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Bears such an emphasis? whose phrase of sorrow

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Conjures the wand’ring stars, and makes them stand

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Like wonder-wounded hearers? This is I,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Hamlet the Dane.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Thou pray’st not well.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: I prithee take thy fingers from my throat;

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: For though I am not splenative and rash,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Yet have I in me something dangerous,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Which let thy wiseness fear. Away thy hand!

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Pluck them asunder.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: Hamlet! Hamlet!

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: All.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: Gentlemen!

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Good my lord, be quiet.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Why, I will fight with him upon this theme

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Until my eyelids will no longer wag.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: O my son, what theme?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: I lov’d Ophelia; forty thousand brothers

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Could not, with all their quantity of love,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Make up my sum. What wilt thou do for her?

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: O, he is mad, Laertes.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: For love of God forbear him!

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: ’Swounds, show me what thou’lt do:

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Woul’t weep? woul’t fight? woul’t fast? woul’t tear thyself?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Woul’t drink up eisel? eat a crocodile?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: I’ll do’t. Dost thou come here to whine?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: To outface me with leaping in her grave?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Be buried quick with her, and so will I.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: And if thou prate of mountains, let them throw

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Millions of acres on us, till our ground,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Singeing his pate against the burning zone,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Make Ossa like a wart. Nay, an thou’lt mouth,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: I’ll rant as well as thou.

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: This is mere madness:

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: And thus awhile the fit will work on him;

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: Anon, as patient as the female dove,

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: When that her golden couplets are disclos’d,

SPEAKER: QUEEN
TEXT: His silence will sit drooping.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Hear you, sir;

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: What is the reason that you use me thus?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: I lov’d you ever. But it is no matter.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Let Hercules himself do what he may,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: The cat will mew, and dog will have his day.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: I pray thee, good Horatio, wait upon him.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Strengthen your patience in our last night’s speech;

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: We’ll put the matter to the present push.—

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Good Gertrude, set some watch over your son.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: This grave shall have a living monument.

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: An hour of quiet shortly shall we see;

SPEAKER: KING
TEXT: Till then in patience our proceeding be.

SPEAKER: SCENE II
TEXT: A hall in the Castle.

SPEAKER: SCENE II
TEXT: Enter Hamlet and Horatio.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: So much for this, sir. Now let me see the other;

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: You do remember all the circumstance?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Remember it, my lord!

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Sir, in my heart there was a kind of fighting

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: That would not let me sleep. Methought I lay

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Worse than the mutinies in the bilboes. Rashly,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: And prais’d be rashness for it,—let us know,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Our indiscretion sometime serves us well,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: When our deep plots do pall; and that should teach us

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: There’s a divinity that shapes our ends,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Rough-hew them how we will.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: That is most certain.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Up from my cabin,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: My sea-gown scarf’d about me, in the dark

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Grop’d I to find out them; had my desire,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Finger’d their packet, and in fine, withdrew

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: To mine own room again, making so bold,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: My fears forgetting manners, to unseal

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Their grand commission; where I found, Horatio,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Oh royal knavery! an exact command,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Larded with many several sorts of reasons,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Importing Denmark’s health, and England’s too,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: With ho! such bugs and goblins in my life,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: That on the supervise, no leisure bated,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: No, not to stay the grinding of the axe,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: My head should be struck off.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Is’t possible?

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: But wilt thou hear me how I did proceed?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: I beseech you.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Being thus benetted round with villanies,—

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Or I could make a prologue to my brains,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: They had begun the play,—I sat me down,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Devis’d a new commission, wrote it fair:

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: I once did hold it, as our statists do,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: A baseness to write fair, and labour’d much

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: How to forget that learning; but, sir, now

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: It did me yeoman’s service. Wilt thou know

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: The effect of what I wrote?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Ay, good my lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: An earnest conjuration from the King,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: As England was his faithful tributary,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: As love between them like the palm might flourish,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: As peace should still her wheaten garland wear

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: And stand a comma ’tween their amities,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: And many such-like ‘as’es of great charge,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: That on the view and know of these contents,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Without debatement further, more or less,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: He should the bearers put to sudden death,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Not shriving-time allow’d.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: How was this seal’d?

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Why, even in that was heaven ordinant.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: I had my father’s signet in my purse,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Which was the model of that Danish seal:

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Folded the writ up in the form of the other,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Subscrib’d it: gave’t th’impression; plac’d it safely,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: The changeling never known. Now, the next day

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Was our sea-fight, and what to this was sequent

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Thou know’st already.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: So Guildenstern and Rosencrantz go to’t.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Why, man, they did make love to this employment.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: They are not near my conscience; their defeat

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Does by their own insinuation grow.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: ’Tis dangerous when the baser nature comes

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Between the pass and fell incensed points

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Of mighty opposites.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Why, what a king is this!

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Does it not, thinks’t thee, stand me now upon,—

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: He that hath kill’d my king, and whor’d my mother,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Popp’d in between th’election and my hopes,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Thrown out his angle for my proper life,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: And with such cozenage—is’t not perfect conscience

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: To quit him with this arm? And is’t not to be damn’d

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: To let this canker of our nature come

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: In further evil?

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: It must be shortly known to him from England

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: What is the issue of the business there.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: It will be short. The interim is mine;

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: And a man’s life’s no more than to say ‘One’.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: But I am very sorry, good Horatio,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: That to Laertes I forgot myself;

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: For by the image of my cause I see

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: The portraiture of his. I’ll court his favours.

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Into a tow’ring passion.

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: Peace, who comes here?

TEXT: Enter Osric.

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: Your lordship is right welcome back to Denmark.

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: No, my good lord.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Thy state is the more gracious; for ’tis a vice to know him. He hath

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: much land, and fertile; let a beast be lord of beasts, and his crib

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: shall stand at the king’s mess; ’tis a chough; but, as I say, spacious

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: in the possession of dirt.

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: Sweet lord, if your lordship were at leisure, I should impart a thing

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: to you from his Majesty.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: I will receive it with all diligence of spirit. Put your bonnet to his

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: right use; ’tis for the head.

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: I thank your lordship, ’tis very hot.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: No, believe me, ’tis very cold, the wind is northerly.

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: It is indifferent cold, my lord, indeed.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Methinks it is very sultry and hot for my complexion.

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: Exceedingly, my lord; it is very sultry,—as ’twere—I cannot tell how.

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: But, my lord, his Majesty bade me signify to you that he has laid a

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: great wager on your head. Sir, this is the matter,—

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: I beseech you, remember,—

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: Nay, in good faith; for mine ease, in good faith. Sir, here is newly

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: come to court Laertes; believe me, an absolute gentleman, full of most

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: excellent differences, of very soft society and great showing. Indeed,

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: to speak feelingly of him, he is the card or calendar of gentry; for

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: you shall find in him the continent of what part a gentleman would see.

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: divide him inventorially would dizzy th’arithmetic of memory, and yet

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: extolment, I take him to be a soul of great article and his infusion of

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: such dearth and rareness as, to make true diction of him, his semblable

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: is his mirror and who else would trace him his umbrage, nothing more.

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: Your lordship speaks most infallibly of him.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: The concernancy, sir? Why do we wrap the gentleman in our more rawer

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: breath?

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: Sir?

SPEAKER: HORATIO

SPEAKER: HORATIO
TEXT: really.

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: Of Laertes?

SPEAKER: HORATIO

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: OSRIC

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: OSRIC

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: OSRIC
TEXT: I commend my duty to your lordship.

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: turn.

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HORATIO

TEXT: If your mind dislike anything, obey it. I will forestall their repair

SPEAKER: HORATIO

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: a sparrow. If it be now, ’tis not to come; if it be not to come, it

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: This presence knows, and you must needs have heard,

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: How I am punish’d with sore distraction.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: What I have done

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: That might your nature, honour, and exception

SPEAKER: HAMLET
TEXT: Roughly awake, I here proclaim was madness.

SPEAKER: HAMLET
